Communicate Data Findings - Pisa 2012 Results Data¶

by Gurps Rai¶

‘What is important for citizens to know and be able to do?’¶

This is the underlying question that the Programme for International Students Assessment (Pisa), tries to answer.

Pisa attempts to understand the range and scope of keys skills that have been acquired by 15 year-old-students, across 65 countries (34 OECD member countries, and 31 partner countries), that are deemed crucial for full participation in modern societies. The Pisa assessment focuses on reading, mathematics, science, and problem solving, along with a whole host of other matrices, that are deemed to have an effect on educational achievement.

The publication of the Pisa report allows policy makers around the world to understand key skills and knowledge that students (at age 15) have acquired both in their own countries, and other countries too, allowing them to learn from policies and practices used elsewhere.

Structure of the dataset¶

The Dataset is very large, and thorough. In total there are 636 features in the dataset, for over 485K students. All columns are in Object (text) type, and looking through the first few lines of the data, I found a mix of both numerical and categorical data. The dataset will need to be reduced, with the correct types applied to those features which I believe can aid me as part of my investigation.

N.B. To determine the main features of interest of the dataset, I used the Data Dictionary$^{1}$ that accompanied the Pisa 2012 dataset - a copy of which can be downloaded from the link in the accreditations below.

Main features of interest¶

I am interested to understand the effects various features of the dataset may have on student academic performance in the three main subject disciplines which are included in the Pisa dataset; Mathematics, Reading and Science.

Dataset features to aid investigation¶

Due to the depth of information provided by the Pisa dataset, I have decided to focus my efforts on the following features:

  • Country of student
  • Wealth of students family
  • Gender
  • OECD membership of country
  • Truancy
  • Immigration status
  • Student possession of textbooks

Overview of dateset features¶

  • Wealth, column represents an index of family wealth. This is based on student responses to their family possessions (i.e. do they have their own room, link to the internet, dishwasher, DVD, number of mobile phones, televisions, computers, cars, etc). This Wealth index can provide me with an indicative relative wealth score that I can use to provide comparisons for my analysis.
  • PVMATH, PVREAD, PVSCIE with each feature have scores ranging from 1-5. I can take an average of the five plausible levels for each discipline, to derive a mean score for each subject that I can then use as part of my investigation.
  • 'ST08Q01,ST09Q01,ST115Q01' (Truancy), has three features within the dataset; if the student skips a class, a whole day, or is late for school. For my investigation, I will only consider truancy levels of those students which skip a whole school day (ST09Q01).
  • 'IMMIG' (Immigration), has three values; native, first generation, and second generation.
  • 'ST04Q01' (Gender), has two values; male or female.
  • 'OECD' has two values; OECD member, or non-OECD member. OECD membership should help to determine a countrys relative wealth, with member countries likely to be richer than non-members$^{2}$.
  • 'ST26Q10' (Possession of Textbooks), has two values; if student possesses textbooks, or not.
  • 'CNT' (Country), contains the name of the students's resident country.

I expect wealth and country of residence to have strong effects on student accomplishment. With greater family and country wealth likely to see higher students scores for the three main subject disciplines of mathematics, reading and science.

Further, I also want to find what effects gender, truancy, and immigration status play, and to see if having possession of something as cheap as a textbook may have an impact on a student's score.

    x= df_group.Mean_Maths_Score[i]
    y= df_group.Wealth[i]
    plt.scatter(x,y)
    plt.text(x+2, y+0.005, country, fontsize=11)

# add crosshairs to chart: overall mean maths score as a vertical line, and overall mean

ax.text(540,-2.5,"Below Average Wealth & Above Average Maths Score",color="blue",size="12")

From this new re-worked scatter plot, we now find the countries at each data point. The most interesting positions are those countries that fall in the two quadrants highlighted above (above average wealth and below average maths scores, and below average wealth and above average maths scores), and in particular those countries which deviate most from the correlated values. Here we find one of the least wealthy countries Vietnam, whose students have above average maths scores. Hong Kong, China and Korea also follow the same trend of below average wealth and above average maths scores. Qatar on the other hand has the complete opposite effect, having the unenviable position of having one of the lowest average maths scores, though it is one of the wealthiest countries in the Pisa data.

Relationships observed between main features of interest.¶

As may be expected, there was found to be a very strong positive linear correlation between my main dependent variables of mean scores. In other words, if you did well in one of the subjects you were likely to do well in the other subjects too. A weak positive correlation was also found between wealth and score, though I needed to investigate this effect further.

There some interesting correlations between gender and the three subject scores. Female students do a lot better on the reading scores than male students, this was seen to be true across the whole range of data. Male students seem to do slightly better than female students in the upper band of scores in mathematics and science (though also slightly worse in the lower range of scores in science), however, female students are more likely to achieve average score across all three subjects i.e. they have less variance across the scores.

Students having textbooks were highly correlated with higher scores for all three subjects. There is no doubting the improvement that textbooks made on scores.

Immigration status did not seem to be correlated to the scores for any of the subjects, and I decided not to follow up on this enquiry for remainder of my investigation.

A very strong correlation was found to exist between a countrys OECD membership and scores. OECD member countries had higher scores for all three subjects than non-members. This was interesting to me, as OECD member countries are understood to be richer$^{2}$ than non-members, and how a countrys wealth may affect student scores, was one of my main initial enquiries.

Truancy was found to be negatively correlated with student scores, the higher the truancy level, the lower the student was likely to score across all of the three subjects.

Other interesting observations.¶

To investigate the weak positive correlation I had initially found between country wealth and scores, I decided to take the average student wealth for each country, and each countrys corresponding maths scores. Mapping each country to a plot, I found some very interesting outliers. Vietnam for example, one of the poorest countries was found to have above average maths scores, and Qatar, one of the wealthiest countries was actually found to have one of the lowest maths scores in the data!

# create heat maps with seaborn's PairGrid.
def hist2dgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    palette = kwargs.pop('color')
    bins_x = np.arange(100, 900+10, 10)
    bins_y = np.arange(-7, 5+.3, 0.3)
    plt.hist2d(x, y, bins = [bins_x, bins_y], cmap = palette, cmin = 0.5)

Finally for this section, I want to look at how textbook possession is correlated to the scores of all three subjects, in relation to the gender of the students.

We find some interesting results here. There seems to be a correlation of textbook possession, gender of students, and the corresponding score of the three subjects. Female students see a greater increase of scores, compared to male students, in mathematics and science if they have textbooks. Male students improve their reading scores more than females if they are in possession of textbooks.

Multivariate relationships observed.¶

The multivariate exploration confirmed some of my earlier findings, but also gave insights to other effects which were of interest to me.

I found OECD membership is not only correlated to a countrys maths score, but also provides a good indicator of a countrys wealth.

Truancy appeared to be correlated to scores and not wealth as I had thought.

Some countries were found to buck the trend of gender in relation to score achieved across the three subjects. Female students were found to outperforming male students in mathematics and science in some countries. However, this may also have been in part to male students underperforming in those countries.

Surprising interaction of features.¶

There seems to be a correlation of text book possession, gender of students, and the corresponding score of the three subjects. In mathematics and science, female students have a greater increase of scores, than male students, if they have textbooks, and male students improve their reading scores more than females if they are in possession of textbooks.
